{"title_page": "Beja, Portugal", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n| official_name   = Beja\n| image_flag      = Pt-bja1.png\n| image_shield    = BJA.png\n| image_skyline           = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a                 = Castelo de Beja 2 (cropped).JPG\n| photo2a                 = Beja Nostra Senora de Concei\u00e7ao.JPG\n| photo2b                 = Castelo de Beja - Muralha interior (cropped).jpg\n| photo3a                 = Beja Torre de Menagem.jpg\n| photo3b                 = Pra\u00e7a da Republica, Beja (1) (cropped).jpg\n| photo3c                 = Beja-37-1-stmaria-feira (cropped).jpg\n| spacing                 = 2\n| position                = center\n| color_border            = white\n| color                   = white\n| size                    = 280\n| foot_montage            =\n}}\n|coordinates             = {{coord|38|02|N|7|53|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n| image_map       = LocalBeja.svg\n|region             = [[Alentejo]]\n|CIM                = [[Baixo Alentejo (intermunicipal community)|Baixo Alentejo]]\n|district           = [[Beja District|Beja]]\n|parishes           = [[#Parishes|11]]\n| leader_party            = [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|PS]]\n<!-- *** Codes ***  -->\n| leader_name             = Paulo Ars\u00e9nio\n| area_total_km2          = 1146.44\n| population_total        = 35,854\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| holiday        = [[Ascension Day]] (date varies)\n| website                 = http://www.cm-beja.pt\n}}\n'''Beja''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8b\u025b\u0292\u0250|-|Pt-pt Beja FF.ogg}}) is a city and a [[List of municipalities of Portugal|municipality]] in the [[Alentejo]] region, Portugal. The population in 2011 was 35,854,<ref>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica]. Ine.pt. Retrieved on 2015-10-27.</ref> in an area of {{cvt|1146.44|km2}}.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The city proper had a population of 21,658 in 2001.<ref>[http://dev.igeo.pt/atlas/Cap2/Cap2d_2.html UMA POPULA\u00c7\u00c3O QUE SE URBANIZA, Uma avalia\u00e7\u00e3o recente \u2013 Cidades, 2004] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006143612/http://dev.igeo.pt/atlas/Cap2/Cap2d_2.html |date=October 6, 2014 }} Nuno Pires Soares, Instituto Geogr\u00e1fico Portugu\u00eas (Geographic Institute of Portugal)</ref>\n\nThe municipality is the capital of the [[Beja District]]. The present Mayor is Paulo Ars\u00e9nio, elected by the [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|Socialist Party]] with an absolute majority in the [[2017 Portuguese local elections|2017 Portuguese Local Elections]].<ref>[https://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/interior.aspx?content_id=1387966&seccao=Sul Beja \u2013 PS conquista C\u00e2mara \u00e0 CDU com maioria absoluta] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213041254/http://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/interior.aspx?content_id=1387966&seccao=Sul |date=December 13, 2013 }} Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias, October 2009. Retrieved June 2012</ref> The municipal holiday is [[Ascension Day]]. The [[Portuguese Air Force]] has an airbase in the area \u2013 the [[Beja Airbase|Air Base No. 11]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pelourinhodebeja2006.jpg|thumb|170px|left|[[Pillory]] in the republican square (''Pra\u00e7a da Rep\u00fablica'').]]\n[[File:Beja45.jpg|thumb|170px|left|Replica of the window where the famous nun [[Mariana Alcoforado]] spoke with the [[No\u00ebl Bouton de Chamilly|Marquis of Chamilly]].]]\nSituated on a {{convert|277|m|ft|adj=on}} hill, commanding a strategic position over the vast plains of the Baixo [[Alentejo]], Beja was already an important place in antiquity. Already inhabited in [[Celtici|Celtic]] times,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/310734/La_contribution_de_la_prospection_g%C3%A9omagn%C3%A9tique_pour_la_compr%C3%A9hension_de_la_pal%C3%A9oforme_de_Matabodes_Beja_Portugal_ La contribution de la prospection g\u00e9omagn\u00e9tique pour la compr\u00e9hension de la pal\u00e9oforme de Matabodes (Beja, Portugal) | Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 Marques da Silva]. Academia.edu (1970-01-01). Retrieved on 2015-10-27.</ref> the town was later named ''[[Pax Julia]]'' by [[Julius Caesar]] in 48 [[BCE]], when he made peace with the [[Lusitanians]]. He raised the town to be the capital of the southernmost province of [[Lusitania]] (Santar\u00e9m and Braga were the other capitals of the ''conventi''). During the reign of emperor [[Augustus]] the thriving town became '''Pax Augusta'''. It was already then a strategic road junction.\n\nWhen the [[Visigoths]] took over the region, the town, then called Paca, became the seat of a [[bishop]]ric. Saint Apr\u00edgio (died in 530) became the first Visigothic [[bishop of Paca]]. The town fell to the invading [[Umayyad]] army in 713. Thus ''Paca'', through Arabic ''Baja'' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0627\u062c\u0629}}), became ''Beja''.\n\nStarting in 910 there were successive attempts of conquest and reconquest by the Christian kings. With the collapse of the Umayyad [[Caliphate of C\u00f3rdoba]] in 1031, Beja became a [[taifa]], an independent Muslim-ruled principality. In 1144 the governor of Beja ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0627\u062c\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0632\u064a\u062a}}), Sidray ibn Wazir, helped the rebellion of the ''[[Mur\u012bd\u016bn]]'' (disciples) led by Abul-Qasim Ahmad ibn al-Husayn al-Quasi in the [[Algarve]] against power of [[Seville]]. In 1150 the town was captured by an army of the [[Almohad dynasty|Almohads]], who annexed it to their North African empire. It was retaken in 1162 by Fern\u00e3o Gon\u00e7alves, leading the army of the Portuguese king [[Afonso I]]. In 1175 Beja was recaptured again by the Almohads. It stayed under Muslim rule till 1234 when king [[Sancho II of Portugal|Sancho II]] finally recaptured the town from the Moors.\n\nAll these wars depopulated the town and gradually reduced it to rubble. Only with [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel I]] in 1521 did Beja again reach the status of city. It was attacked and occupied by the Portuguese and the Spanish armies during the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] (1640\u20131667).\n\nBeja became again the head of a [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beja|bishopric]] in 1770, more than a thousand years after the fall of the Visigothic city. In 1808 [[Napoleon]]ic troops under General [[Jean-Andoche Junot|Junot]] sacked the city and massacred the inhabitants.\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Climate===\nDue to its southernmost location with the descending winds of the subtropics, low precipitation, especially in summer and far from the coast makes the city a [[Mediterranean climate|hot-summer Mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Csa'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=85620&cityname=Beja,+Portugal|title=Beja, Portugal K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> and therefore is the hottest city of [[Portugal]] and one of the hottest of the [[Iberian Peninsula]] in the maximum temperatures. Between 2001 and 2018 it had the hottest summer of any city in the country, hotter than other cities like [[\u00c9vora]], [[Lisbon]] or [[Porto]]. Although mild by European standards, Beja has relatively cool winters, while summers are long and hot. The high in January is around {{convert|14|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} while the July and August highs are around {{convert|33|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. [[Snow]] is rare but may occur on a few occasions in a century, the last being on January 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jn.pt/sociedade/interior/nevao-deixou-a-regiao-de-beja-branca-1069971.html|title=Nev\u00e3o deixou a regi\u00e3o de Beja branca|website=www.jn.pt|language=pt|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> The January low is {{convert|5|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and in July and August is {{convert|16|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. The annual mean is around {{convert|17|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. The average total rainfall in a year is {{cvt|558|mm}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pureviagem.com.br/noticia/portugal-conheca-as-belezas-da-regiao-do-alentejo_a18983/9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030094549/http://www.pureviagem.com.br/noticia/portugal-conheca-as-belezas-da-regiao-do-alentejo_a18983/9|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-10-30|title=Beja: Considerada o lugar mais quente de Portugal, Beja \u00e9 uma cidade super grac|date=2017-10-30|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publico.pt/2018/09/24/sociedade/noticia/as-cidades-europeias-estao-mais-quentes-portugal-esta-no-fim-da-lista-1844739|title=As cidades europeias est\u00e3o mais quentes. Portugal est\u00e1 no fim da lista|last=Costa|first=Rita Marques|website=P\u00daBLICO|language=pt|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dspace.uevora.pt/rdpc/handle/10174/18343|title=Climatologia e qualidade da \u00e1gua na Bacia Hidrogr\u00e1fica do Guadiana|last=Potes|first=Miguel Joaquim Fernandes|date=2008|website=dspace.uevora.pt|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"ipma\" /> The year 2005 was particularly dry in [[Portugal]] and '''Beja''' suffered devastating forest fires in the surrounding rural areas which contributes to [[desertification]] in the [[Alentejo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publico.pt/2009/11/19/jornal/alentejo-pode-estar-a-caminho-da-pior-seca-de-sempre-18247298|title=Alentejo pode estar a caminho da pior seca de sempre|last=Dias|first=Carlos|website=P\u00daBLICO|language=pt|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/cm-ao-minuto/detalhe/mais-de-5-mil-com-falta-de-agua|title=Mais de 5 mil com falta de \u00e1gua|last=Manha|first=Correio da|website=www.cmjornal.pt|language=pt-PT|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n{{Weather box    \n| width        = 100% <!-- 77% if there is a template or image next to it -->\n| collapsed    = y <!-- y, if you have normal updates -->\n| open         = \n| metric first = y <!-- always, except UK or US cities -->\n| single line  = y\n| location     = Beja (Santiago Maior), elevation: {{convert|247|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}, 1961-1990 normals and extremes\n<!--in the order as it appears in the table, not all of the following data may be available, especially records and days of precipitation -->\n| Jan mean C  =9.6\n| Feb mean C  =10.4\n| Mar mean C  =11.9\n| Apr mean C  =13.7\n| May mean C  =16.9\n| Jun mean C  =20.8\n| Jul mean C  =23.8\n| Aug mean C  =24.0\n| Sep mean C  =22.2\n| Oct mean C  =17.7\n| Nov mean C  =13.0\n| Dec mean C  =10.1\n| Jan high C =13.8    \n| Feb high C =14.9    \n| Mar high C =17.3    \n| Apr high C =19.4    \n| May high C =23.7    \n| Jun high C =28.4    \n| Jul high C =32.5    \n| Aug high C =32.5    \n| Sep high C =29.3    \n| Oct high C =23.2    \n| Nov high C =17.5    \n| Dec high C =14.2  \n| Jan record high C  =22.0\n| Feb record high C  =24.1\n| Mar record high C  =28.8\n| Apr record high C  =29.8\n| May record high C  =36.7\n| Jun record high C  =43.3\n| Jul record high C  =42.7\n| Aug record high C  =41.4\n| Sep record high C  =42.0\n| Oct record high C  =34.3\n| Nov record high C  =28.1\n| Dec record high C  =21.2\n| Jan low C  =5.4    \n| Feb low C  =5.9    \n| Mar low C  =6.6    \n| Apr low C  =7.9     \n| May low C  =10.1     \n| Jun low C  =13.2     \n| Jul low C  =15.1     \n| Aug low C  =15.4     \n| Sep low 