913 and worked in [[vaudeville]] and [[repertory theatre]]. He acted in the original productions of ''Excuse Me'' written by [[Rupert Hughes]] (later adapted twice for the screen) and ''[[Oh! Oh! Delphine]]''.<ref name=than/>\n\nCurran was signed to a three-year contract by the [[Thanhouser Company]] in 1915 and made 22 films, including ''[[The World and the Woman]]'' with [[Jeanne Eagels]] and ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]'', the first non-pornographic American film to show full female nudity. In his later years he moved to California and made his living playing [[bit part]]s and small roles in [[Film studio|studio]] films. His last film appearance was as [[Theodore Roosevelt|Teddy Roosevelt]] in the \"News on the March\" sequence in ''[[Citizen Kane]]''. The film had not yet been released when Curran, aged 61, died in [[Hollywood]] on January 24, 1941.<ref name=than>{{cite web|url=http://www.thanhouser.org/tcocd/Biography_Files/ind9jxyin.htm|title=Thomas A. Curran Biography|publisher= [[Thanhouser Company|thanhouser.org]]|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 260\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    =Audrey Munson1.jpg\n| alt1     =\n| caption1 =[[Audrey Munson]] and Thomas A. Curran in ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]'' (1915)\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    =The Vicar of Wakefield (1917).webm\n| alt2     =\n| caption2 =[[:File:The Vicar of Wakefield (1917).webm|''The Vicar of Wakefield'']] (1917)\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n| image3    =Citizen-Kane-Whistle-Stop.jpg\n| alt3     =\n| caption3 =Curran (waving hat) as [[Theodore Roosevelt|Teddy Roosevelt]], campaigning with Charles Foster Kane ([[Orson Welles]]) in the \"News on the March\" sequence in ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' (1941)\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''From the River's Depths''\n|\n| <ref name=tha